  "prompt": "Why do I feel sleepy and tired after consuming non-drowsy cold/flu-relief medication?",
  "response": "Feeling sleepy or tired after taking \"non-drowsy\" cold and flu medication can happen for several reasons:\n\n1. **Mild Sedative Effect**: Even medications labeled \"non-drowsy\" can have mild sedative effects in some individuals due to their active ingredients or how they interact with your body.\n\n2. **Underlying Illness**: The cold or flu itself can cause fatigue, and the medication may not completely eliminate this symptom. Your body is still fighting the infection, which can make you feel tired.\n\n3. **Decongestants and Stimulants**: Non-drowsy formulas often contain decongestants like pseudoephedrine or phenylephrine, which are stimulants. In some people, these can cause a \"crash\" once their effects wear off, leading to fatigue.\n\n4. **Dehydration**: Many cold and flu medications can cause mild dehydration, which can make you feel tired and sluggish.\n\n5. **Side Effects**: Even if a medication is marketed as non-drowsy, individual reactions can vary. Your body might metabolize the drug differently, leading to unexpected side effects like sleepiness.\n\n6. **Other Ingredients**: Some medications contain additional ingredients (e.g., antihistamines like loratadine or cetirizine) that can cause drowsiness in sensitive individuals, even if they are generally considered non-drowsy.\n\nIf this happens regularly, consider switching to a different medication or consulting a healthcare professional for advice. Additionally, staying hydrated, getting rest, and supporting your immune system can help reduce fatigue while recovering from a cold or flu.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
